keywords sealed names apparatus midgaard
---
The Sealed Names apparatus was Midgaard's administrative system for processing persons under
restricted legal categories during the Violet Compact era. It assigned classified names to
individuals—persons whose original identities were sealed for administrative purposes—and routed
them through the "resettled south" mechanism to southern frontier settlements, specifically
Rakuen. The apparatus operated at the intersection of several institutional functions: the
Sealed Names classified individuals and suppressed their original identities; the Bell Synod's
satellite witnessing office in Rakuen absorbed and eliminated testimonies from those individuals
that could embarrass the Violet Compact administration; and Midgaard's sealed warrant archive
provided the originating legal authority for the classifications. The apparatus was designed
using welfare-language framing—persons were classified as "resettled" for welfare purposes,
routing them under administrative categories that created documentation obligations without
creating welfare provision obligations. The apparatus is still partially operational within
Midgaard's Continuity faction: active sealed names classifications continue to run through
the same administrative pathways, though the volume is significantly lower than during the
Violet Compact peak period. Rakuen's Garden Ledger holds the most complete surviving external
evidence of the apparatus's operational scope.

flags MIDGAARD
---
The Sealed Names apparatus sits at the center of Midgaard's Continuity/Reckoning factional
divide. The Continuity faction's position: the apparatus was a legitimate emergency administrative
tool for managing population displacement during the Violet Compact period, its classifications
were issued under valid authority, and the records are properly sealed under that authority.
Review of sealed classifications requires demonstrating specific harm to a specifically identified
party, which is structurally difficult when the identities of the classified persons are the
thing that is sealed. The Reckoning faction's position: the apparatus was designed to make its
own accountability impossible to establish—seal the names, disappear the testimonies, and
require identification of sealed persons as a precondition for reviewing why they were sealed.
The circular dependency is not accidental. Midgaard's charter office currently holds approximately
fourteen hundred active sealed classifications under Violet Compact-era authority. The
Continuity faction controls access to the review process; the Reckoning faction controls public
advocacy but not the archive.

flags KOWLOON
---
Kowloon's Black Ledger sits in direct institutional parallel to Midgaard's Sealed Names
apparatus: both are sealed archive systems covering the condemned-debtor transfer operations
of the Spirebound Conclave era. The difference is that Kowloon's Black Ledger—if it exists
as described—covers delta settlement operations, while the Sealed Names apparatus covers the
upstream classification and routing mechanism. Kowloon's Jade Magistracy is aware that if the
Black Ledger were opened, the most useful cross-reference for its entries would be the Sealed
Names apparatus classifications—the upstream records that would establish which classified
persons were routed where. Both cities' Continuity factions have the same interest: neither
archive opens until the other does, because each opening requires the other opening as context.
This perverse solidarity—shared guilt creating shared interest in sealed records—is the
structural reason both archives remain closed.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess's founding charter anti-sealed-warrant clause was written in direct response to the Sealed
Names apparatus model. The clause's specific language—no sealed warrant issued by a predecessor
authority shall bind a Kiess citizen—targets exactly the apparatus's operational mechanism:
sealed classifications issued by a superior administrative authority that bind the classified
person without their knowledge or ability to contest. The Kiess Syndic Council maintains a
formal opinion that Sealed Names classifications applied to persons who subsequently became
Kiess residents are null and void under the charter's anti-sealed-warrant provision. This opinion
has not been tested in formal proceedings because no Sealed Names classified person has yet
presented themselves to Kiess seeking that nullification. The Syndic Council considers the
opinion standing law; Midgaard's Continuity faction considers it an unauthorized nullification
of valid sealed authority. The disagreement is formally active and unresolved.

flags RAKUEN
---
Rakuen's Garden Ledger is the most complete surviving external evidence of the Sealed Names
apparatus's operational scope. The Ledger Clerks have identified three categories of Garden
Ledger entries that correspond to apparatus operations: persons registered under sealed names
without prior welfare classification documents, persons whose welfare classification documents
were issued simultaneously with their registration rather than preceding it, and persons whose
welfare documentation uses standard welfare language but references administrative routing
categories that do not correspond to any welfare program the Clerks can locate in Midgaard's
public records. These three categories together represent approximately four hundred and twenty
persons in the Ledger's Violet Compact-era records. The Clerks have matched approximately
ninety of these persons to Bell Synod witnessing office intake records through cross-reference
with other Garden Ledger entries. The Reckoning faction has twice attempted to use the Garden
Ledger evidence to initiate formal review of the apparatus's classifications. Both attempts
were denied on the grounds that the Garden Ledger's classification of the entries as apparatus-
related has not been verified by cross-reference to the sealed apparatus records.

flags MAFDET
---
Mafdet's Ledger Houses encounter the Sealed Names apparatus when maritime estate claims reference
persons classified under sealed names whose current legal status is unclear. The most common
scenario: an individual arrives in Mafdet with documents indicating a sealed-name classification
from the Violet Compact period and seeks to establish their original identity for property or
inheritance purposes. The Swift Court's position on sealed-name classifications is consistent
with its general approach to Midgaard-issued sealed documents: the classification is acknowledged
as having been issued by a competent authority, but its current effect on legal status under
Strandline Compact jurisdiction requires independent assessment. Mafdet has processed eleven
such cases in the last thirty years; in seven, the claimant produced sufficient corroborating
evidence to establish identity independent of the sealed classification. In four, the claim
was suspended pending resolution of the classification's legal status.

flags MIDGAARD KHENARI
---
Khenari mortuary jurisprudence treats the Sealed Names apparatus as the most serious category
of institutional harm: the administrative destruction of a living person's legal name, which
in Khenari law is equivalent to preventing a soul from being correctly identified at the
threshold of death. If a person dies under a sealed name rather than their true name, the
death record is incorrect. The inheritance chain is disrupted. The debt-settlement process
fails. The soul's legal processing at threshold—which in Khenari practice depends on accurate
death records—is compromised. The nine descent families maintain a specific legal process for
name restoration after institutional classification: it requires presentation of evidence to
a Khenari mortuary tribunal and, if successful, produces a formal Name Restoration Certificate
that supersedes sealed classifications in Khenari-governed legal proceedings. Khenari archivists
have issued seven Name Restoration Certificates for persons whose Sealed Names apparatus
classifications were reconstructed through Garden Ledger cross-reference.

flags MIDGAARD UMBRAL
---
Umbral shadow-archives contain the largest collection of observation records relating to the
Sealed Names apparatus's operational period. Umbral communities near the Gloamvault site
observed the intake and routing of classified persons through Kel'Shadra's institutional
framework, maintaining records of who was observed entering, what documentation was presented,
and—critically—who was not subsequently observed leaving. The intake shadow for Sealed Names
apparatus operations is documented in Umbral records as a specific operational pattern: persons
arriving with welfare classification documents were typically observed entering and not observed
exiting through standard channels. Umbral archives cross-referenced with Garden Ledger entries
have produced the most complete picture of the apparatus's downstream operation. The Reckoning
faction has formally requested access to Umbral observation records for the Violet Compact
period; the Umbral archivist community has agreed to provide access subject to their own
verification of the requesting parties' purposes.

