---
Khenari archivists have been the most effective external researchers on the Sealed Names apparatus
because their mortuary jurisprudence gives them a specific methodology for reconstructing
classified names through death records. If a person died in Rakuen during the Violet Compact
era and was registered under a sealed name, the death record exists in Rakuen's registry under
that name. If the same person's original identity can be established through other records—
family testimony, prior caravan registrations, Khenari mortuary records from their community
of origin—the two records can be cross-referenced to establish that the sealed name and the
original name refer to the same person. This methodology has successfully matched forty-three
Sealed Names apparatus classifications to original identities in the Garden Ledger reconstruction
project. The matches constitute the most concrete evidence currently available of what the
apparatus was actually used for.
